Suggested Story Arc

Instead of random queries, divide project into “business questions.”

That is what analysts actually do.

Example structure:

1. Revenue Overview

Questions:

Which customers generate most revenue?
Which categories sell best?
Are sales stable over time?

Queries:

Top customers
Monthly revenue trend
Best-selling categories

Narrative:

“A small number of customers contribute disproportionately to revenue.”

Classic Pareto stuff. Safe business insight.

2. Operational Problems

Questions:

Are shipments delayed?
Which shippers perform worst?
Are some products sitting unused?

Queries:

Average shipping delay
Products never ordered
Slow-moving inventory

Narrative:

“Several products appear inactive and may represent inventory inefficiency.”

That sounds professional without pretending you discovered capitalism.

3. Employee Performance

Questions:

Which employees handle highest sales?
Are workloads uneven?

Queries:

Employee sales ranking
Orders per employee

Narrative:

“Sales distribution between employees is uneven, though additional staffing/context data would be needed before drawing conclusions.”

Important analyst skill:
not overclaiming from weak data.

4. Customer Behavior

Questions:

Which products are often bought together?
Which customers became inactive?

Queries:

Product pair analysis
Customers with no orders

Narrative:

“Some recurring product combinations may support bundling or recommendation strategies.”

Tiny baby Amazon emerges from the swamp


